The formulation described in the “Mathematical formulation” section can be classified as a combinatorial optimization problem, where the optimal infrastructure layout (topology) results from a finite set of possible infrastructure interventions, i.e., added edges, such as new roads. Figure 1 summarizes the workflow that is used to solve for the final holistic infrastructure expansion.Fig. 1Workflow for obtaining the final infrastructure expansion.
Z is the objective function of the performance-oriented infrastructure expansion optimization problem. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varepsilon$$\end{document}ε is the number of relocations triggered by infrastructure expansion. \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
